<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-983-640  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 983 640.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Today's Office  Oct 1989 v24 n5 p29(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CAR systems: a critical link in information management.(ComputerAssisted Retrieval; includes related article on designer CARs.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Burnacz, Joanne G.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Businesses increasingly use computer-assisted-retrieval (CAR)systems to facilitate location and retrieval of documents storedon microfilm or optical disk.andP;  CAR systems help improve customerservice, provide economical use of space, ensure file integrity,and reduce personnel expense.andP;  Whether based on micro-, mini-, ormainframe computers, software is the driving force behind a CARsystem.andP;  In deciding whether a CAR system is necessary, usersshould consider such issues as file quantity and activity, bothcurrent and projected.andP;  Companies increasingly integrate CARsystems with other technologies, and manufacturers increasinglydesign standards-based, media independent systems.andP;  Applicationsand developments that further enhance the cost effectiveness ofCAR systems are anticipated.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Resources ManagementComputer SystemsSystem Selection.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>